      "content": [
        {
          "type": "text",
          "text": "Perfect! Your counter circuit is ready. Here's the wiring table and operation:\n\n**Wiring Table:**\n\n| Arduino Pin | Component | Function |\n|-------------|-----------|----------|\n| D2 | 7-Segment Display (Segment a) | Display segment control |\n| D3 | 7-Segment Display (Segment b) | Display segment control |\n| D4 | 7-Segment Display (Segment c) | Display segment control |\n| D5 | 7-Segment Display (Segment d) | Display segment control |\n| D6 | 7-Segment Display (Segment e) | Display segment control |\n| D7 | 7-Segment Display (Segment f) | Display segment control |\n| D8 | 7-Segment Display (Segment g) | Display segment control |\n| D9 | Button (Pin A) | Increment button (pulled LOW when pressed) |\n| GND | Button (Pin B) + Display (GND) | Ground return |\n\n**How it works:**\n- **Button press** increments the counter (0–9, then wraps to 0).\n- Each segment is driven through a 220Ω resistor (limits current to ~20mA per segment at 5V).\n- The sketch uses debouncing (20ms delay) to filter noise and detect clean button presses.\n- The 7-segment display updates immediately after each increment.\n\n**Operation:** Press the button to increment the displayed digit. The counter cycles 0 → 1 → 2 → ... → 9 → 0."
        }
      ]
    }
